hook.real_world_problem:
Module 6 taught you this pattern for grouping:

```java
// Group products by category — Module 6 style (7 lines):
Map<String, List<Product>> byCategory = new HashMap<>();
for (Product p : catalog) {
    byCategory.computeIfAbsent(p.getCategory(), k -> new ArrayList<>()).add(p);
}
```

With `Collectors.groupingBy()` — one line:
```java
Map<String, List<Product>> byCategory = catalog.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(Product::getCategory));
```

Same result. One line. And it gets better — want the count per category?
```java
Map<String, Long> countByCategory = catalog.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(Product::getCategory, Collectors.counting()));
```

Average price per category?
```java
Map<String, Double> avgPriceByCategory = catalog.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(Product::getCategory,
        Collectors.averagingDouble(Product::getPrice)));
```

Collectors are the final power tool of the Stream API. After this topic, the complex Map-building patterns from Module 6 become one-liners.

concept_explanation.grouping_by_basic:
**`Collectors.groupingBy(classifier)`** — group stream elements by a key:

```java
import java.util.stream.Collectors;

List<Employee> staff = ...;

// Group by department — Map<String, List<Employee>>
Map<String, List<Employee>> byDept = staff.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(Employee::getDepartment));

// Access the groups:
List<Employee> engineering = byDept.get("Engineering");
List<Employee> sales       = byDept.get("Sales");

// Iterate all groups:
byDept.forEach((dept, employees) -> {
    System.out.println(dept + ": " + employees.size() + " employees");
});
```

The classifier function (here `Employee::getDepartment`) is applied to each element. Elements that return the same value end up in the same group.

**groupingBy replaces** the Module 6 `computeIfAbsent` loop entirely. Every time you see `Map<K, List<V>>` being built with a loop, groupingBy can replace it.

concept_explanation.downstream_collectors:
**Downstream collectors** — process each group further:

```java
// Count per group
Map<String, Long> countByDept = staff.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
        Employee::getDepartment,
        Collectors.counting()              // ← downstream
    ));
// {Engineering=5, Sales=3, Marketing=2}

// Average salary per department
Map<String, Double> avgSalaryByDept = staff.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
        Employee::getDepartment,
        Collectors.averagingDouble(Employee::getSalary)  // ← downstream
    ));

// List of names per department (transform elements before collecting)
Map<String, List<String>> namesByDept = staff.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
        Employee::getDepartment,
        Collectors.mapping(Employee::getName, Collectors.toList())  // map + collect
    ));

// Joined names per department
Map<String, String> joinedNamesByDept = staff.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
        Employee::getDepartment,
        Collectors.mapping(Employee::getName, Collectors.joining(", "))
    ));
```

The second argument to `groupingBy` is the **downstream collector** — applied to each group's elements.

concept_explanation.summarizing_double:
**`Collectors.summarizingDouble()`** — full statistics in one pass:

```java
// Comprehensive salary stats
DoubleSummaryStatistics stats = staff.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.summarizingDouble(Employee::getSalary));

System.out.println("Count:  " + stats.getCount());
System.out.println("Sum:    " + stats.getSum());
System.out.println("Min:    " + stats.getMin());
System.out.println("Max:    " + stats.getMax());
System.out.println("Average:" + stats.getAverage());

// Per department statistics
Map<String, DoubleSummaryStatistics> statsByDept = staff.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
        Employee::getDepartment,
        Collectors.summarizingDouble(Employee::getSalary)
    ));

statsByDept.forEach((dept, s) -> 
    System.out.printf("%s: avg=₹%.0f, max=₹%.0f%n",
        dept, s.getAverage(), s.getMax()));
```

Also: `Collectors.summarizingInt(...)` and `Collectors.summarizingLong(...)`.

concept_explanation.to_map:
**`Collectors.toMap(keyMapper, valueMapper)`** — build a Map from a stream:

```java
// Product ID → Product object
Map<String, Product> byId = catalog.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.toMap(
        Product::getId,       // key function
        product -> product    // value function (or: Function.identity())
    ));

// Product name → price
Map<String, Double> priceByName = catalog.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.toMap(
        Product::getName,
        Product::getPrice
    ));

// Name → transformed value
Map<String, String> upperNameByName = staff.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.toMap(
        Employee::getName,
        e -> e.getName().toUpperCase()
    ));
```

**Duplicate key warning**: if two elements produce the same key, `toMap` throws `IllegalStateException`. Handle with a merge function:

```java
// Merge: if duplicate key, keep higher salary
Map<String, Double> salaryByDept = staff.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.toMap(
        Employee::getDepartment,
        Employee::getSalary,
        (existing, newVal) -> Math.max(existing, newVal)  // merge function
    ));
```

concept_explanation.partitioning_by:
**`Collectors.partitioningBy(predicate)`** — split into exactly two groups (true/false):

```java
// Split into passed/failed
Map<Boolean, List<Student>> result = students.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.partitioningBy(s -> s.getScore() >= 60));

List<Student> passed = result.get(true);
List<Student> failed = result.get(false);

System.out.println("Passed: " + passed.size());
System.out.println("Failed: " + failed.size());

// With downstream: count each partition
Map<Boolean, Long> counts = students.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.partitioningBy(
        s -> s.getScore() >= 60,
        Collectors.counting()
    ));
// {true=8, false=2}

// In stock vs out of stock
Map<Boolean, List<Product>> stockSplit = catalog.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.partitioningBy(Product::isInStock));
```

`partitioningBy` vs `groupingBy`: use `partitioningBy` when there are exactly 2 groups (yes/no, pass/fail, active/inactive). Use `groupingBy` for arbitrary numbers of groups.

concept_explanation.joining_variants:
**`Collectors.joining()`** — all three forms:

```java
List<String> names = Arrays.asList("Aisha", "Raj", "Priya");

// Simple concatenation
String simple  = names.stream().collect(Collectors.joining());
// 'AishaRajPriya'

// With delimiter
String delimited = names.stream().collect(Collectors.joining(", "));
// 'Aisha, Raj, Priya'

// With prefix and suffix
String wrapped = names.stream().collect(Collectors.joining(", ", "[", "]"));
// '[Aisha, Raj, Priya]'

// Practical: SQL IN clause
String inClause = ids.stream()
    .map(String::valueOf)
    .collect(Collectors.joining(", ", "WHERE id IN (", ")"));
// 'WHERE id IN (1, 2, 3)'
```

concept_explanation.groupingby_with_filtering:
**groupingBy with pre-filtering** — filter before grouping or within downstream:

```java
// Filter THEN group
Map<String, List<Employee>> seniorByDept = staff.stream()
    .filter(e -> e.getYearsExp() >= 5)  // filter first
    .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(Employee::getDepartment));

// Group then filter within downstream (Collectors.filtering — Java 9+)
Map<String, List<Employee>> seniorByDept2 = staff.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
        Employee::getDepartment,
        Collectors.filtering(e -> e.getYearsExp() >= 5, Collectors.toList())
    ));

// Multi-level grouping: department → city → employees
Map<String, Map<String, List<Employee>>> byDeptCity = staff.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
        Employee::getDepartment,
        Collectors.groupingBy(Employee::getCity)  // nested groupingBy
    ));
```

Multi-level grouping creates nested maps. Powerful but use judiciously — beyond 2 levels it gets hard to read.

